{
    "level": "B1",
    "intro": "In this topic you will learn how to match common intensifiers with adjectives and adverbs: <strong>very, really, so, too, absolutely, quite, rather, pretty</strong>.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "GRADABLE",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "With ordinary gradable adjectives, we often use <strong>very / really / pretty / quite</strong>.",
            "example": "very cold / really good / quite busy"
        },
        {
            "label": "STRONG",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "With strong adjectives, <strong>absolutely / completely / totally</strong> often sounds more natural.",
            "example": "absolutely amazing / completely impossible"
        },
        {
            "label": "TOO",
            "color": "amber",
            "text": "<strong>Too</strong> means “more than wanted / more than is good”.",
            "example": "too expensive / too late"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Common intensifiers",
    "intro": "It helps to know both the meaning and the usual collocations.",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "normal strengthening",
            "title": "very / really / pretty / quite",
            "subtitle": "very busy, really happy, pretty good, quite small"
        },
        {
            "label": "strong adjective",
            "title": "absolutely / completely / totally",
            "subtitle": "absolutely amazing, completely wrong"
        },
        {
            "label": "too much",
            "title": "too + adjective",
            "subtitle": "too noisy, too heavy, too late"
        },
        {
            "label": "sufficient amount",
            "title": "adjective + enough",
            "subtitle": "warm enough, fast enough"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. How to choose the natural word",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Very, really, so, quite",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "These words often come before <strong>gradable adjectives</strong> and adverbs.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "It is very cold today.",
                    "ua": "It is very cold today."
                },
                {
                    "en": "She is really friendly.",
                    "ua": "She is really friendly."
                },
                {
                    "en": "The room was quite small.",
                    "ua": "The room was quite small."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Absolutely, completely, totally",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "These intensifiers often work better with <strong>strong adjectives</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "The view was absolutely amazing.",
                    "ua": "The view was absolutely amazing."
                },
                {
                    "en": "That answer is completely wrong.",
                    "ua": "That answer is completely wrong."
                },
                {
                    "en": "I am totally exhausted.",
                    "ua": "I am totally exhausted."
                }
            ],
            "note": "Phrases such as <em>very amazing</em> are possible, but often less natural."
        },
        {
            "label": "Too and enough",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "<strong>Too</strong> has a negative idea, while <strong>enough</strong> shows sufficiency.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "This bag is too heavy.",
                    "ua": "This bag is too heavy."
                },
                {
                    "en": "The water is warm enough now.",
                    "ua": "The water is warm enough now."
                },
                {
                    "en": "He is not old enough to drive.",
                    "ua": "He is not old enough to drive."
                }
            ],
            "note": "Remember the order: <strong>too + adjective</strong>, but <strong>adjective + enough</strong>."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. Common mistakes",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Mistake 1",
            "color": "rose",
            "title": "Using very with a strong adjective.",
            "wrong": "The film was very amazing.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">The film was absolutely amazing.</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 2",
            "color": "amber",
            "title": "Using too instead of very.",
            "wrong": "The food is too good.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">The food is very good.</span> <span class=\"text-slate-500\">(if the meaning is positive)</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 3",
            "color": "sky",
            "title": "Wrong position of enough.",
            "wrong": "The room is enough big.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">The room is big enough.</span>"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "4. Quick summary",
    "items": [
        "<strong>Very / really / quite / pretty</strong> often go with ordinary gradable adjectives.",
        "<strong>Absolutely / completely / totally</strong> often match strong adjectives.",
        "<strong>Too</strong> means more than wanted and often has a negative meaning.",
        "<strong>Enough</strong> comes after the adjective: <em>warm enough</em>.",
        "Choose the intensifier not only by strength, but also by the kind of adjective."
    ]
}

